<br>
     &quot;Why, tis the younglings bickering amongst themselves, trying to impress the unimpressable watchers, the Lords of Neriak.  If you wish to find favor in the city, it might be wise to go join in the fray.&quot;  The young one swore he could see laughter in the guards eyes, even through his concealing helm.<br>
<br>
     &quot;Bah, must I?&quot;  He shook his head.  &quot;I have no desire to impress anyone with my talents.  I know what I am capable of, and do not need to impress any but the Great Lord himself.  All the same, i do need to work on the fighting skills necessary for advancement in my guild.&quot;  He turned slowly, a look of resignation on his not-quite-delicate features.  The guard paused for a moment, and then hailed the younger elf.<br>
<br>
    &quot;Who are you, youngling, and of what house do you belong?&quot;<br>
<br>
    The younger one paused, and then slowly turned around, his face set in a grimace/smirk that gave the much more experienced guard a chill right down his spine.  &quot;My name, sir, is Shaiith, and as to my house...&quot;  All traces of amusement disappeared, leaving nothing but a mask of pain and hatred.  &quot;I have no house, sir, but the house the Necromancers gave me.&quot;  With that, he turned once more, set his spine straight, and ran off with nary a look back toward the noise and commotion.<br>
<br>
     'No house,' the guard wondered, 'no house and... Shaiith?  Nameless?  What secrets do you hold, young Nameless Knight?'  After a few moments of thought, the guard shrugged at his sentry partner and went back to his vigil.<br>
