<br>
     Breathing in the fresh air, he gave a rare smile.  His hair, dyed a light shade of grey, blew gently in the breeze.  The night was calm, and dark for those without gifts such as his.  He almost felt sorry for them, these... humans.  Almost.  the darkness, with barely a sliver of moon to light it, was much brighter than any light he had ever seen before.  It mattered not to him.  His skills and expertise were as such that the Great Lord was almost ready to grant him his spells.  This was good.  More ways he could bring suffering to the races that embraced the light.<br>
<br>
     As if on cue, a movement caught his eye.  Cursing his own ineptitude, the young dark elf quickly cloaked himself in a veil of non-seeing, which allowed him to remain hidden even though an observer might pass but two paces near.  He took in the sight, and chuckled.  A lone elf, a warrior by the look of him, wearing leather armor and carrying a sword that looked a little fine for one so young, even by the elven standards of quality.  This one had friends in high places, and his presence here was probably an initiation of sorts.  It was almost certain he was being watched from afar.  Shaiith quickly gauged his opponent, and found him worthy.  Smiling to himself, he waited for an opportune moment to make his presence known.<br>
<br>
     He didn't have to wait long.  The elf turned and looked behind him, attempting to watch his back and make sure he wasn't taken from behind.  That was never Shaiith's intention.  With a feral grin in place, he dropped the concealing cantrip and chuckled softly.  The effect was instantaneous.<br>
<br>
     The pale one spun around so fast he nearly fell, and snapped into a familiar fighting position.  Shaiith chuckled again, realizing that this was no warrior.  This was what the wood elves called a ranger, a druid who took up the blade.  He studied his opponents features, committing them to memory, wanting to remember what his first kill looked like with his head still intact.  He saw the pale brown hair, eyes the color of the leaves on the trees, and a beautiful face that was now drawn into a tight, pensive expression of wariness.  With a start, Shaiith realized that his opponent was female!  He chuckled again and shrugged.  Male, female, it made no difference to him.  If they wore a sword with the intention to use it, as this one did, then they were dead.  Gender meant little.<br>
<br>
     On the elf's part, as she studied her opponent who had seemingly come out of nowhere, She saw an elven face, but with bluish black skin, and the features were twisted into what could only be called a sneer of contempt.  By human standards, this one was still handsome, but to her aesthetic eye, his face was too course, the eyebrows too thick, the nose too narrow, giving the dark one a predatorial look.  She had no doubts as to what- or who - his prey was.<br>
<br>
     No visible or audible sign was heard, but one moment they stood facing each other, and in the next there was a flash of steel, a loud clash, and muttered curses as the dark figure drew back, holding his arm above the elbow.  Crimson drops stained the burnished bronze armplates as he inspected the wound.  He nodded:  he could still fight.<br>
<br>
     Throwing himself suddenly into a headlong dive at her feet, he rolled with his blade angled slightly out, hoping to at least nick her legs.  The pale one was too quick, and jumped over the hurtling form, performing a frontflip an acrobat would have been proud of.  Coming down lightly, she spun, thrusting her sword at where the shape had been.   It wasn't there, and the tip sunk into the soft earth.  A flurry of movement ahead told her what had happened:  the dark elf hadn't stopped rolling after the initial attack.  Now the tip of his great sword was shooting towards her chest, hoping to remove her heart.  She accepted the worst of the blow, but turned aside.  The resulting wound was painful, but not lethal.  She wasn't done.<br>
<br>
     Feinting a thrust, she quickly stopped just short of her target, switching the maneuver into a downward chop that caught the dark one completely off guard.  The blade passed within inches of his head, scoring deeply into his shoulder.  With surprising speed, he stood and stepped back a pace.  That last attempt had nearly been the end of him.  It was all he could do to maintain a defense against the blows that came fast and furious now.<br>
<br>
     Desperation lent Shaiith strength, but he knew the outcome of this battle.  He would die, his body be left for the scavengers, and anything of value on him would be taken.  Suddenly, he felt the old surge of hatred.  This harmful touch had saved his life in the past, and now he called upon it again.  Throwing every last ounce of strength into his next few blows, he managed to strike the pale one repeatedly, scoring hits on shoulder, chest, and thigh.  Weakened, the elf staggered back out of range of that deadly blade.  Not far enough.<br>
<br>
     Lunging at his opponent as she retreated, the young Knight of shadows let the hatred build, burn, and boil its way through his body.  Focusing the energy as his mentor had taught him, he slammed his fist into the delicate bone structure of the elven wench's face.  The hatred flowed to a focal point in his hand, and with the familiar hissing whine and stench of ozone, the young elven female's face exploded into a fine red mist.  The corpse dropped lifelessly to the soft ground, a small pool of red slowly growing larger around the fallen head.<br>
<br>
     Clutching his wounded shoulder, Shaiith again called the veil of shadows and crumpled next to his fallen foe.  <br>
<br>
     Darkness came.<br>
<br>
