t</span><hr size=1> He moved.  At a dead sprint, he moved.  <br>
He wasn't fast enough.<br>
<br>
The pale imitation of himself he had been chasing ran faster than he had any right to.  The elf stopped briefly, allowing Shaiith to get a bit closer, and muttered something under his breath.  Instantly, the boots he was wearing glowed brightly, and he took off again.<br>
<br>
Curses!  Damn the foul creature!  Where did they get this equipment from?  Inevitibly the wood elves and high elves that came within reach of his blade were somehow hastened, through the use of those damnable boots or the spells they cast or the songs they sang.  One day, he would show them.  He would show them all.<br>
<br>
Maybe what was needed was a visit to their own home, a little greeting from him to them.  He chuckled darkly to himself as he watched the pathetic elf vanish into the evening mist of the commonlands.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, a swarm of insects converged upon him from out of nowhere, biting at him, and attempting to get to the blood beneath the ebon skin.  It was irritating, aggravating, annoying, and it downright bloody pissed him off, but he knew enough to hold his anger down and look around for the source of the pests.<br>
<br>
Not there... not there... THERE! <br>
<br>
The voice in the back of his head screamed at him.  NOW!  STRIKE NOW!<br>
<br>
This was only the second time he had heard it, but so far, it's desires and his were one and the same.  He struck.  Knowing that this scourge of pests would eventually bleed him down a bit, he struck with the lifestealing spell, allowing him a few precious moments of relief before the maddening bugs drained the new blood out as well.  More was called for.  He didn't feel like chasing this one down, so he called upon another of his powers, and the diminuitive figure was surrounded by darkness, slowing his steps.<br>
<br>
Shaiith chuckled even as he ran towards his assailant.  Try to take HIM by surprise, eh?  Fine.  He wondered for a moment what the person on the receiving end of a two-handed sword felt right before it cut into him.  His preoccupation was abruptly cut short, as the roots from the short bushes somehow leaped up out of the ground and wrapped arounnd his legs, fastening him firmly and causing a little bit of pain as well.<br>
<br>
Snarling, no longer even slightly amused, he ripped his way out of the grasping roots and hurtled towards his opponent.  Spells, eh?  Well, two could play that.  <br>
<br>
Pausing for a moment, he caused his mind to be filled with sickness and disease, and directed the sensation mentally towards his foe.  The halfling, for so it was, turned decidedly pale and shook his head as if to clear it.  By that time, Shaiith was upon him.<br>
<br>
Almost shrieking his hate, the dark Knight swung the sword in a large arc, slashing deep into the druid's arm.  The druid staggered back a bit, shook his head again, tested the arm for durability, and pulled from his belt a wicked-looking scimitar.  Shaiith stepped back a pace and began another spell.  This small creature had no need for the strength to use said weapon, at least in his eyes, and he could always use more.<br>
<br>
Upon completion of the spell, the halfling weakened a bit, and Shaiith grinned, feeling the weight of the two handed sword grow less in his hand.<br>
<br>
NOW!  STRIKE NOW!<br>
<br>
Again the voice bellowed in his head.  That, he thought, wasn't really necessary, because that was exactly what he was doing.  Even as he thought, the heavy blade went above his head and came screaming down towards the halfling.<br>
<br>
Obviously knowing little of swordplay, the druid put up his blade to attempt to at least cushion the blow.  The steel of the scimitar was not made to take the kind of force that was being dealt, however, and snapped like a twig under the weight of the heavier blade.  The arm underneath, bracing, didn't fare too well either.  As a matter of fact, it was nearly sheared clean off.<br>
<br>
Realizing suddenly (a little late) that he was not as good a swordsman as the dark one, the druid fell back on something he knew.  Magic.  Muttering, gesturing, and pointing at the dark elf, he began to emanate flames from his fingertips.<br>
<br>
     &quot;I don't think so, my boy,&quot;  Shaiith hissed.  &quot;It must be very hard to concentrate with the hilts of a sword shoved where the sun doesn't shine!&quot;  So saying, he drew back to attack again, the voice inside screaming at him to strike NOW, while he was vulnerable.  &quot;Curse you, be silent, I DO know what i'm doing here!&quot;  The halfling paused.  Who had the Tier'dal been speaking to?  Great Mother, not only was he dangerous, he was quite mad as well!<br>
<br>
The delay cost him.  Dearly.  As he watched the dark elf converse with thin air, he forgot in his untimely interest the fact that there was over a full meter of steel headed directly towards his head.<br>
<br>
At least, until it got there.  After that, he didn't have to worry about anything ever again.<br>
<br>
Shaiith thrust the blade into the soft ground a few times to clean the blood off, knocked off a few loose clods of dirt, and proceded to slice the druid's purse strings.  Nothing.  Such cheap bastards.  If they were going to come attack him, they should really hit up the bank before they came.  All the same, his lesson had been learned.  He would certainly be more attentive in the future.  The last of the swarm departed, leaving the Knight of Shadows alone with his thoughts.<br>
