<br>
Besides, he was headed for other parts, and didn't really have time to stop and play.<br>
<br>
Walking briskly through the tunnel, the slim figure he made casting little shadow in the darkness, Shaiith soon came upon an opening to his right.  He glanced in, and noted the presence of several merchants.  This was odd.  A collection of merchants that didn't seem to dislike him... yet the large hollowed out section of cavern was completely void of anyone except the merchants.  Under any other circumstances, the hawkers would be bawling their wares, trying to be heard over the din of a massive crowd.<br>
<br>
He walked in, and went around to several of the merchants to see what they had in stock.  As he had thought, he found nothing but the basic items.  These merchants hadn't seen a lot of business in a long while, perhaps even never.  It was a shame; it was in a fairly ideal spot, and the merchants looked like they would do business with any and all who stepped into their areas.  <br>
<br>
Walking out, his gaze fell on a shadowy form, right near the entrance.  Something about the figure screamed rascal, yet there was something compelling about him.  Shaiith shrugged.  It would be compelling to someone besides him.  He didn't really care.  At all.<br>
<br>
Continuing down the wide stone corridor, he thought again about what he had to do in Grobb.  What did he have to do?  Nothing, really.  Maybe check out the Knights' chapter there, although it was doubtful they had anything worth anything.  They were, after all just trolls.  He wondered again why the older Knights had wanted him to go.  Maybe just to get him out of their hair.  It made sense.  They thought they were so wonderful, wise beyond belief in their experience.  Hm.  What did they know.  Hells, Grobb didn't even bother keeping back the jungle, from what he had heard.<br>
<br>
Coming to the end of the tunnel, Shaiith wished that he was in the jungle now.  It was hot, and dry, and dry, and hot, and everywhere there was sand.  Not the beach sand that he was used to seeing in the rich houses, this was fine, gritty desert sand  It was so light even a slight breeze could pick it up and deposit it in places one didn't even know existed, let alone be able to hold something that irritating for that long.<br>
<br>
And the sun!  He had never seen the sun so bright.  It glared at him, daring to come out and risk the rays of heat.  Nature was one thing, and then again deific directions were something else entirely.  &quot;That which does not kill me...&quot;<br>
<br>
He took the sun's dare, and stepped out of the tunnel.<br>
<br>
And immediately stepped back into it.  Maybe after nightfall he would cross.<br>
<br>
The day wore on, and the air grew dryer, and the sand grew grittier, and there came a point where Shaiith stopped sweating.  He had sweat all the moisture right out of his body.  And this was in the shade!!  Downing yet another canteen of water, the young dark elf checked his rapidly dwindling supply.  It was time to move, sun or not.  If he stayed here for too long, he would be too far away from another spot for water to make it to alive.  He wondered morbidly how much of a wind it would take to push his dessicated body across the sands like a tumbleweed.<br>
<br>
He hadn't travelled very far at all when he began to smell salt in the air, and began to see trees ahead of the cliff face he was walking by.  As he got closer he realized... there was another entrance to Freeport!  There, looking at him apprehensively, but not doing anything that would be considered a threat to his wellbeing, was a merchant!  Water!  He wouldn't die out here after all.  At least not of thirst.<br>
<br>
His pack now feeling much more satisfyingly heavy, Shaiith walked on, leaving a very relieved looking merchant and two glowering guards behind.  Following the smell of salt, he walked on, until he came to a little outpost that seemed to be made for fishing.<br>
<br>
It was right on the edge of a vast expanse of water, greater than any he had ever seen before.  This must be the ocean the books spoke of.  The voice in the back of his head chuckled at his wonderment.  It was the first he had heard it since his encounter with the halfling.  'Who are you?  WHAT are you?' he said mentally.  He had a good idea, but there were a lot of powers that could do the same.  No response forthcoming, he started down the coast.  <br>
<br>
It was a long, long walk.  All he could see in the distance were dunes, sand, dunes, and more sand.  It didn't really matter too much to him.  Nothing seemed to anymore.  He tried to feel sorry about that, but nothing came.  Nothing at all.  Shaiith shrugged, and continued on his way. <p>Gruuz Grimeyfingurz, Craknek uv da Lex Invictus fambly... pikklez er guud wit cheez.</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub37.ezboard.com/blexinvictus.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=gruuzgrimeyfingurz>GruuzGrimeyfingurz</A> at: 3/6/02 3:22:18 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub37.ezboard.com/unanookt.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nanook T</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Ph3aR my witty sig</span><br>  Posts: 316<br> <font color=#70DB93>(3/8/02 6:52:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub37.ezboard.com/flexinvictusfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=51.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Saga Continues: Ro</span><hr size=1> Good stuff Gruuz!  I can feel the desolation..<br>
