<br>
More curious than anything, he stood and was about to investigate when something niggled the back of his mind.  Not the Voice, not this time, but something else...  Caution?  He wondered at that, but decided to listen to his instincts.  Bowing his head and pulling two small white fragments from his pack, he concentrated, spoke a few words, and dropped the fragments on the ground.  Nothing happened for a few seconds, but suddenly the fragments began to grow.  They elongated and branched, and in the space of a few breaths a skeletal warrior stood before him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Guarding you, Master.&quot;  it said in a voice straight from a crypt.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, I suspected you might,&quot;  the knight said, smiling wryly.  His defense in place, he darted lithely across the desert sands, his minion keeping a careful distance behind him.<br>
<br>
The cries he had heard in the distance were beginning to sound desperate, and he hastened his steps, if only to see the demise.  Cresting a dune, he involuntarily stopped in awe.  A troll, a green creature easily twice his height and many times his weight, was doing battle with a crocodile, such as the ones he had seen moving sluggishly along the coast.  This particular specimen, how ever, was not sluggish in the slightest.  It was also very, very large.  The only thing that had saved the troll so far, it seemed, was the brave fight it was putting up.  The croc's head was so huge, it could have easily swallowed the troll whole.  A name came back to him, from one of the guild's books...<br>
<br>
LockJaw.<br>
<br>
This troll was in trouble, and although LockJaw was wounded in several places, if the warrior didn't receive aid soon, he would become a meal for this vast reptile.  Shaiith thought a moment, then reached into a pocket and pulled out a copper.<br>
<br>
&quot;Heads you're in luck, tails you're lunch.&quot;  The coin spun up into the air.<br>
<br>
Gazing down at the shiny image of one of Neriak's council of elders, the knight shrugged his shoulders.  &quot;I could have sworn that was a double tail coin, but I guess I grabbed the wrong one.  Besides, maybe you can help me get to Grobb.&quot;  Leaving the coin where it lay, Shaiith rushed down the slope, shouting to his minion to attack.<br>
<br>
He paused right before he got to the monstrous beast, which served two purposes.  One, the pet got there before him, and took a little of the brunt of any attacks headed his way.  Two, it gave him time to lay down a mystical offense.  Fearing the monster's great strength, the knight drained it for himself.  Not noting any great discomfort, he wondered briefly what he had gotten himself into, and launched his next attack.  Drawing upon that well of sickness again, he threw it mentally at the beast, and was stunned when it didn't even flinch!  The magic hadn't affected it in the slightest!  Growling in his throat, he drew his sword and launched himself with reptilian strength at his target- the neck.<br>
<br>
He was very glad he had taken the strength when he had, because the damage he did was minimal.  If he hadn't taken it, he likely wouldn't have been able to scratch the surface of the monster's skin.  Muttering in frustration, he attempted to call the sickness again, and met with results this time.<br>
<br>
The result was LockJaw's animosity.<br>
<br>
Meanwhile, the troll, seeing assistance, buckled down and started to throw his axe around, causing some serious injuries on the reptile's side.  This drew LockJaw's attention back to the troll, but not before leaving grievous wounds on the dark elf.<br>
<br>
Not really concerned, Shaiith drew again on his power to drain life, healing himself, and deepening some scratches on the monster in the bargain.  He looked at his skeletal warrior, sighed at the fact that it hadn't done ANY damage whatsoever, and then took stock of the situation.  He was surprised when he saw the froth flecking from the trolls lips, and the glazed look in his eyes.  He had reached a state where he knew he was going to die, and didn't care.  If he was going down, then this creature was going down with him.<br>
<br>
Now, that didn't suit Shaiith's purpose at all.  He needed this creature to survive, if only to show him to Grobb.  After that point, the dark elf really didn't care what happened to the smelly warrior.<br>
<br>
The troll started chanting in a foreign language, a warrior's death song in his native tongue, probably.  Shaiith shook his head.  This would not do at all!  The dark knight stood back and gauged his foe's remaining life, and found that there was only one way to defeat the monster before the troll died.  He moved back in, with great sweeps of his sword that the troll would have applauded had he been in any condition.  Shaiith grabbed hold of LockJaw's tail and drove his sword into it, as deeply as it would go.  THAT got the beast's attention.<br>
<br>
Pivoting much more swiftly than anything that size had a right to, Lockjaw snapped at this irritating little creature.  It had a dull form of intelligence, and it recognized that many more blows like that could conceivably cause it serious harm.  So it did what any normal, self-respecting giant crocodilian would do.  It snapped at the thing that had struck from behind it.<br>
<br>
NOW! NOW! NOW! NOW!<br>
<br>
Barely pausing long enough to mutter a sarcastic &quot;No, really?&quot;, Shaiith reached into that now-familiar well of hatred and anger.  As the great jaws came crashing inexorably down, a diminutive fist flew up to meet it.  A hissing whine, a stench of ozone, and a powerful explosion blew the entire top part of the beast's head clean off.  The body did a complete somersault, nearly landing on the still-frothing troll.  The warrior continued to mindlessly hack at the carcass, still chanting, still swinging.<br>
<br>
Shaiith shook his head.  He was going to have to wait for the battle frenzy to wear off.  He looked over at his skeletal minion, who was untouched.  Small wonder, he hadn't caused any damage, why would he have taken any?  The dark elf sighed, and muttered &quot;Back to hell with you!&quot;  The minion bowed its head in submission.<br>
<br>
&quot;As you command, O great one.&quot;  At least it was polite.  Mist began to rise from the bones, and in no time, nothing that remotely looked like a skeleton remained.  Even the footprints began to blow away in the sand.  Shaiith sat down and began to meditate again, confident that anything stupid enough to venture near would go for the raging troll first.<br>
